<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="jn1032a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="jn1" href="#jn1032">JN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/jn1all.htm#jn1032a"> (NLI.2A) 32(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <p class="spbr">~ said to be beautiful in so far as it encounters the activity of simple perception.</p> <p class="spbr"> Sensible objects, however, are said conventionally to be beautiful or not for neither of the foregoing reasons but rather by reason of the nature, degree and duration of the satisfaction resulting from the apprehension of them and it is in accordance with these latter merely that the words &ldquo;beautiful&rdquo; and &ldquo;ugly&rdquo; are used in practical esthetic philosophy. It remains then to be said that these words indicate only a greater or less measure of resultant satisfaction and that any sensible object, to which the word "ugly" is practically applied, an object, that is, the apprehension of which results in a small measure of esthetic satisfaction is, in so far as its apprehension results in any measure of satisfaction whatsoever, said to be for the third time beautiful . . . . .</p> <p class="duup"> JAJ</p> <p class="duup"> Pola.15.XI.04.</p> </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: Continued from <a name="jn1031a" href="jn1all.htm#jn1031a">JN1 (NLI.2A):031(a)</a>.</mm> </dd></dl>
